\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb360\sa200\li0\ri0\f1\fs48\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Font Sizes\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 In the world of typography, font sizes are usually expressed in units of \i points\i0 , where 1 point equals about 1/72 inch. Thus, when text is drawn at a certain font size, this is usually meant as an absolute value: the vertical distance between the descender and ascender, as shown here:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_3.eps \width3200\height900
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 So, a font size of 18 points corresponds to about a quarter of an inch.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Although Calliope also defines font size in terms of the height from the descender to the ascender, Calliope does not attach any physical measurement to font size alone.  Instead, Calliope uses a unique method, called \i relative units\i0 , for specifying the sizes of fonts.  All font sizes are understood as being relative to a \i design size\i0  which is ultimately based on the height of the normal staff chosen for the document.  The physical font size will depend on the physical height of the staff.  The advantages of this method are:\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	It is easy to establish `design rules' based on the desired proportions between graphic elements of the notation.  This can give a coherent appearance to the document.\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	It is not necessary to change font sizes of individual text objects when staff sizes are changed or scaled.  Because the sizes of characters are always rendered relative to the normal staff size, this dramatically reduces the amount of editing required when making changes to the layout and scaling of a document. Thus, regardless of various formatting and adjustments made by the user, Calliope will automatically maintain the `design rules'  without further input from the user.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 With Calliope it is possible to specify default font sizes for the following items independently:\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	Text underlay\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	The `figures' used in figured bass notation.\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	Tablature characters\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	Bar (`measure') numbers\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The defaults may be overridden on an individual basis if necessary.  In addition, font sizes are used to specify the size of characters for labels, system headers, staff headers, and running page headers and footers..\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 For all these objects (except running page headers and footers), font sizes are expressed in \i relative units\i0 .  Although these units are for convenience specified in points, these are not ordinary points, and will be called \i relative points,\i0\i0  or just points.  The reference unit is the staff height chosen for normal-sized staves in the document:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0   {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_2.eps \width5720\height1540
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The unit staff height is defined to be \i 32 relative points\i0 , regardless of its physical size.  The Document Preference panel provides a means for specifying the physical staff height of the unit staff on the page.  The font sizes of all text (except for running page headers and footers)  are expressed in points \i relative\i0  to the the unit staff.  Thus, when text underlay is defined as having a font size of 18 points, this means that the font size relative to the staff size will be 18 / 32, or about 56% of a unit staff height.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 For text underlay, the important design parameter is not the font size, but the \i cap height\i0  ± the height of the capital letters above the baseline ± as shown above.  The cap height depends on the precise design of the font used.  For example, the cap height of New Century Schoolbook, used for the `A' underlay in the above example, is 72.2% of the font size.  For Times Roman the cap height is 66.2% of the font size.  Therefore, with the example above having a text underlay font size of 18 relative points, the cap height will be (18 ´ 0.722) / 32, or about 40% of the staff height.  The \i actual\i0  size will depend on the staff height chosen by the user.  Similarly, the cap height of Times Roman at 18 relative points is calculated as 37% of the staff height. Experimentation has shown that text underlay cap heights in the range 37-40% are both legible and well proportioned to the staff, and therefore 18 relative points is a sensible default value for text underlay.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The default `design' values chosen for the text objects are as follows:\par
